To be honest and direct: **This is not actually a linked list.**

What you have written is a **Wrapper Class for an Array**. While your code is valid JavaScript and functions correctly as a list, it does not implement the data structure or the performance characteristics of a Linked List.

### Why this isn't a Linked List
In computer science, a **Linked List** is defined by how it stores data in memory:
1.  **Nodes:** Data is stored in discrete "Node" objects.
2.  **Pointers:** Each node contains a reference (pointer) to the *next* node in the sequence.
3.  **Non-contiguous:** Unlike arrays, nodes do not need to be next to each other in memory.

Your implementation uses a JavaScript **Array** (`[]`). In JavaScript, arrays are dynamically resized, contiguous blocks of memory (or optimized to behave that way). By using `this.data.push` and `this.data.splice`, you are just using the built-in array methods.

---

### The "Real" Linked List Implementation
To build a true linked list, you first need a `Node` class, and then a `LinkedList` class that manages those nodes.

```javascript
class Node {
    constructor(value) {
        this.value = value;
        this.next = null; // This is the "link"
    }
}

class LinkedList {
    constructor() {
        this.head = null;
        this.size = 0;
    }

    // Add to the end: O(n) - must traverse to the end
    add(value) {
        const newNode = new Node(value);
        if (!this.head) {
            this.head = newNode;
        } else {
            let current = this.head;
            while (current.next) {
                current = current.next;
            }
            current.next = newNode;
        }
        this.size++;
    }

    // Get by index: O(n) - must walk the chain
    get(index) {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.size) return null;
        let current = this.head;
        for (let i = 0; i < index; i++) {
            current = current.next;
        }
        return current.value;
    }

    // Remove by index: O(n)
    remove(index) {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.size) return null;

        let removedNode;
        if (index === 0) {
            removedNode = this.head;
            this.head = this.head.next;
        } else {
            let current = this.head;
            let previous;
            for (let i = 0; i < index; i++) {
                previous = current;
                current = current.next;
            }
            removedNode = current;
            previous.next = current.next;
        }
        this.size--;
        return removedNode.value;
    }
}
```

