### Comparison: Your Version vs. Real Linked List

| Feature | Your Implementation (Array) | Real Linked List |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Memory** | Contiguous block | Scattered (Nodes + Pointers) |
| **`get(index)`** | **$O(1)$** (Instant access) | **$O(n)$** (Must walk from the start) |
| **`add(item)`** | **$O(1)$** (Amortized) | **$O(n)$** (Unless you keep a `tail` pointer) |
| **`remove(0)`** | **$O(n)$** (Must shift all other items) | **$O(1)$** (Just update the `head` pointer) |

### Detailed Feedback on your code:

1.  **Naming:** If you intend to use an array, call the class `List` or `Collection`. Calling it `LinkedList` will confuse other developers because they will expect $O(1)$ insertion/deletion at the head, which arrays don't provide.
2.  **Abstraction:** Your implementation is a "leaky abstraction." It doesn't add any value over a standard JavaScript array; in fact, it's less powerful because it hides useful methods like `map`, `filter`, and `forEach`.
3.  **Performance:** In your version, `remove(index)` uses `splice()`. If you remove the first element of a 1,000,000-item array, JavaScript has to re-index the remaining 999,999 items. In a real Linked List, you just move the `head` pointer, which is nearly instantaneous.

### Summary
If you are practicing for **interviews or learning data structures**, you should rewrite it using the `Node` pattern shown above. 

If you just wanted a **utility class** to hold data, your code works fine, but you should just use a standard JavaScript Array directly, as it is highly optimized by the V8 engine.
